Text.Value: I'm already starting to regret making that deal with him.
Don't worry - the boss treats his clients right. He's as honest as his life is long.
Who are you, exactly?
Same kind of people who'd ask about it. Folks with a death wish.

EditorData.NodeContext: stern warning - she's telling us to shut up

Text.Value: I won't pretend he's an altruist. But he's looked at the balance sheet - no world, no souls.
Have you ever been tempted to earn some extra coin selling infernal secrets?
As a noose. Doesn't stop people from testing it, though.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'As a noose' is a response to 'security must be tight'. Proudly. She helps out with that security

Text.Value: You know, I think I did miss Raphael.
Yes, you do - and what better place to do business than in the home of the oldest trade?

EditorData.NodeContext: cheerful - 'the oldest trade' is a reference to the brothel she's drinking in

Text.Value: Enough of this - enjoy your drink, and think of lighter things.
No interest in meeting up with devil scum.
Go see Raphael - then I might let you buy me a drink.
Hahaha. Excellent.
He should have stayed home - I have no intention of speaking with him.
I'm insulted you'd even suggest that.
Whatever you need to tell yourself, honey. Deep down you know the truth. And so do I.
Speaking of Raphael - did you miss his invitation? He's waiting for you in Sharess' Caress.
I think I made a bad choice.
Better to feast in the Hells than go begging in the Heavens.
Who are you, exactly?
Damn, Hoots. That new batch burns stronger than a pit fiend's fist.

EditorData.NodeContext: talking to the bartender, impressed by the strength of the drink she has just finished (no need to show her drinking it)

Text.Value: Gortash must have had help from someone with infernal connections. Any idea who?
Doesn't matter why. My word is final - no deal.
When he's there, yes. But he's a busy man - contracts and interests in many places, and on many planes.
I hope things turn out well for you, I really do. Cheers.

EditorData.NodeContext: sadly - she knows (but we don't) that things won't turn out well at all

Text.Value: Listen - because I'll only say this once - this fight isn't just about Baldur's Gate, or the Sword Coast, or even Faern.
A toast to Raphael's latest client, the saviour of the city.
I'm not Raphael's client. He's my pawn.
More than anything. My old dwarven master used to beat me and feed me scraps - Raphael treats me right and feeds me well.

EditorData.NodeContext: cheerful - explaining why she likes working for a devil

Text.Value: I'm not for sale. My time's not for sale. My affection's not for sale. I'm here on other business.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: hasn't looked up from her mug yet - is muttering darkly, she's clearly said this to a lot of people who've assumed she's a prostitute (she's standing at the bar in a brothel)

Text.Value: He knows me - and you - better than that. You should reconsider his offer.
We meet again.
Good to see you again, even if you have put me out of pocket. The boss bet me five soul coins you'd reach the city in one piece.

EditorData.NodeContext: cheerful - she bet against us surviving in a 'playful' wager, but is glad to see us nonetheless

Text.Value: I'll take that as a compliment.

EditorData.NodeContext: smiling, referring to somebody reacting strongly to a drink you just poured them

Text.Value: You've put me out of pocket, you know. Raphael bet me five soul coins you'd reach the city in one piece.
He rented a room upstairs in the hope that you'd drop by.
Something's off about this one. On your guard.
I'm still considering my options.
He'll be in Sharess' Caress in Wyrm's Crossing. Go, now, if you know what's good for you - and the world.
When I'm not keeping my eye on potential clients like you, I make sure the House of Hope is fully secure.
I would never.

EditorData.NodeContext: surprised by an accusation of treachery

Text.Value: Devils often have prettier hoards than dragons. Sneaking thieves into their vaults is a lucrative business - doesn't usually end well for the thieves.

EditorData.NodeContext: cheerful, but the last phrase has a trace of annoyance. She doesn't like these 'thieves'

Text.Value: We'll celebrate together in the House of Hope when the victory's won.
He's a devil. It's his nature. He needs to get his due.
If that prick Gortash came nosing around my turf, I'd tell him to stick his gauntlet where the sun don't shine.
Leave.
Oh! You must have slipped by me earlier. Raphael's very disappointed you turned him down.
Korilla is my name. I'm Raphael's... assistant, shall we say.
I'll go see him - we have unfinished business.
I'm sure you're right. Between the dictators, the murderers, the Guild, and the cult, the city's brimming with goodness.
He should have stayed home - I have no intention of speaking with him.
Maybe I rejected him too hastily.
Take your time - have a drink, sample the goods. Go see him when you're feeling refreshed.
We meet again.
Raphael can stop it - he wants to - and he knows how. You're the key. You always have been.
Then go un-miss him. And hurry up. Devils are patient by nature, but even Raphael has certain limitations.
He wants to help you save the world. What else?

EditorData.NodeContext: as if it's the most obvious thing in the world

Text.Value: Yeah - a diabolist with a loose sense of duty, and a hunger to be richer than Mammon.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bitterly. She is all about duty. 'Mammon' is an archdevil.

Text.Value: But sometimes the thieves are rich, smart, or well-connected enough to come back in one piece. Take our esteemed Lord Gortash, for example.

EditorData.NodeContext: not dropping her cheerful persona, but with some real venom for Lord Gortash. She really doesn't like him

Text.Value: What does he want with me?
Security must be tight.
Did he tell you to try and win me over with your charms?
The boss might be a devil, but he'll treat you more honestly than anyone else in the city.
C'mere - I'm not going to start an argument. I just want to know why you turned the boss down.
We meet again.
Hah, are you joking? Because I hate him.
I can't wait to get back to the hells - at least it's warm there. The wind off the harbour here cuts me to the bone.

EditorData.NodeContext: she's sincere about this, despite how ludicrous it might sound

Text.Value: Oh! It's Raphael's favourite misadventurer.
What exactly is it you do for him?
Conversation's over. I've got to sober up and get back to work.

EditorData.NodeContext: stern warning - she's telling us to shut up

Text.Value: We meet again.

I doubt it - but even if you do, you won't survive the fight.
I'd reconsider if I were you.
Take it however you want, but I'll be having my usual from now on.

EditorData.NodeContext: talking to a bartender, just drank a particularly powerful shot and you're impressed but will NOT be drinking it again

Text.Value: I am. You can save yourself and the city if you sign that contract.
And it's hard to get leverage on an illithid - they make terrible clients.

EditorData.NodeContext: with a smile, trying to make light of a serious situation

Text.Value: He's gutted you know - had such high hopes for you.
Don't keep Raphael waiting.
You've made his century, you know. You're going to save us, Baldur's Gate - everyone, he says.
Seen sense yet? Raphael's still waiting. He can still help you get through this.
Ah, I forget we've never met. I've had my eyes and ears on you so long, we feel like old friends.
I'll stop the brain without his help.
There you are. I'd almost lost track of you. Almost.
Bullshit.
You definitely didn't.

EditorData.NodeContext: Piping up when the player says 'Maybe I rejected Raphael too easily'

At least hear him out - you'll be surprised by what he has to offer.
What does he want with me?
Then why make demands of me instead of just helping?
Who are you, exactly?

Oh! Raphael's latest client - saviour of the city, he says!
Did he tell you to try and win me over with your charms?
Maybe you're right.
What exactly is your job?
Such a shame - you won't survive without his help, and I'll miss your pretty face.
The boss is always right. Even though he's so very wrong.

Cheeky. We might be in a brothel, but I'm not that kind of gal. You should reconsider, though.
